Arrays in Java – Theory
Definition
An array in Java is a collection of elements of the same data type, stored in contiguous memory locations.
It allows you to store multiple values in a single variable instead of declaring separate variables for each value.
Syntax
dataType[] arrayName = new dataType[size];
or
dataType[] arrayName = {value1, value2, value3, ...};
Example:
int[] marks = new int[5];
int[] numbers = {10, 20, 30, 40, 50};
Accessing Elements
Each element in an array is accessed using its index number.
Indexing starts from 0.
Example:
System.out.println(numbers[0]); // prints 10
System.out.println(numbers[4]); // prints 50
Input and Output of Arrays
Scanner sc = new Scanner(System.in);
int[] arr = new int[5];
for (int i = 0; i < 5; i++) {
    arr[i] = sc.nextInt(); // input
}
for (int i = 0; i < 5; i++) {
    System.out.println(arr[i]); // output
}
Types of Arrays

1. Single-Dimensional Array – A simple list of elements.
Example: int[] a = {1, 2, 3, 4, 5};


2. Multi-Dimensional Array – An array of arrays (like a matrix).
Example:

int[][] matrix = {
    {1, 2, 3},
    {4, 5, 6}
};
Common Array Operations
Operation	Description	Example
Traversal	Accessing each element	Loop through array
Insertion	Adding an element (usually by creating a new array)	—
Deletion	Removing an element (shift or new array)	—
Searching	Find position of an element	Linear / Binary search
Sorting	Arrange elements	Bubble, Selection, Insertion sort
Advantages
Easy to store and access multiple values.
Reduces code size.
Efficient for fixed-size data collections.
Limitations
Fixed size (cannot be increased dynamically).All elements must be of the same data type.
Insertion and deletion operations are complex compared to ArrayList.
Example Program
class ArrayExample {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int[] arr = {10, 20, 30, 40, 50};
        for (int i = 0; i < arr.length; i++) {
            System.out.println("Element at index " + i + ": " + arr[i]);
        }
    }
}
Output:
Element at index 0: 10
Element at index 1: 20
Element at index 2: 30
Element at index 3: 40
Element at index 4: 50
